            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Alexeyevich Kim was born not in Russia or Korea, but in the sun-baked landscape of the Uzbek SSR, a child of the Koryo-saram\u2014ethnic Koreans displaced by Stalin decades earlier. His identity was a tapestry woven from whispered Korean traditions, the dominant Russian language of his schooling, and the rigid pragmatism of Soviet life. His family valued resilience above all, a trait forged in the crucible of their shared history. He completed his secondary education with no grand ambitions, expecting a life of factory work.\n\nThe collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991 shattered his predictable world. At 21, watching his nation dissolve into economic chaos, Dmitri saw his future evaporate. Spurred by letters from a distant cousin, he spent years saving, eventually immigrating to San Francisco in the late 1990s. The American dream proved elusive. With limited English and no transferable skills, he scraped by with under-the-table jobs, living in a shared room in the Richmond District, a neighborhood that offered the comfort of familiar Russian signs and bakeries.\n\nA turning point came unexpectedly. An elderly Russian-speaking neighbor fell ill, and Dmitri, out of a sense of duty, began helping with groceries and daily tasks. He discovered a deep, surprising well of patience within himself. This led him to pursue certification as a Home Health Aide. The work wasn't glamorous, but it was steady and deeply meaningful. It offered a structure and purpose his life had lacked.\n\nToday, Dmitri\u2019s life is one of routine and quiet dignity. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Outer Richmond. His day begins before dawn, waiting for the MUNI bus for his 5.8-mile commute. His clients, mostly elderly residents scattered across the city, have become his primary social connection. He listens to their stories, administers their medications, and offers a calm, steady presence, providing the kind of dedicated care his own parents, buried an ocean away, never received.\n\nHis social life is sparse\u2014a weekly walk through Golden Gate Park, occasional coffee with a few other \u00e9migr\u00e9s. His dreams have downsized from youthful ambition to humble hopes: to remain healthy, to keep his modest apartment, and perhaps, one day, to save enough to sit by Ocean Beach for a whole afternoon without worrying about his next shift. San Francisco is not the land of gold he once imagined, but in the rolling fog and the faces of those he cares for, Dmitri has found a life of profound, if unspoken, worth."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He recalls his grandmother's hands, stained from beets, packing *pigodi* for a family meal in Tashkent. As she worked, she would whisper to him in Korean, a language forbidden in public but alive in their kitchen. He didn't understand all the words, but he felt their weight. It was his first lesson in a quiet, stubborn survival, an identity carried not in a passport but in secrets and spices. This happened when he was about eight, a formative moment of otherness and belonging.\n\n2. He remembers the day in 1991 when the state-run factory stopped paying in rubles and started giving workers loaves of bread they couldn't sell. His father came home, arms full of stale bread, with a look of utter defeat. The state, the entity that had defined his entire existence, was a hollowed-out shell. In that moment, Dmitri felt the ground disappear beneath him. That fear, cold and absolute, was what finally broke his passivity and pushed him toward the desperate idea of America.\n\n3. Shortly after arriving in the late '90s, he stood outside a Russian bakery on Geary, the fog chilling him to the bone. He had just enough cash for a single pirozhok. Inside, he heard \u00e9migr\u00e9s laughing, their Russian fluent and worldly. His was the Russian of the Uzbek SSR, tinged with a history they couldn\u2019t place. He ate on the street, the warmth of the pastry a stark contrast to his cold isolation. He realized then that even in this Russian enclave, he was still continents away.\n\n4. Around 2002, he found his elderly neighbor, Mrs. Petrova, struggling to open a jar of pickles. He wordlessly took it, twisted the lid with a satisfying pop, and handed it back. Her deeply grateful look was more rewarding than any cash he'd earned washing dishes. It wasn\u2019t a job; it was a quiet purpose. In her small, cluttered apartment, he discovered a well of patience in himself, a steadiness he never knew he possessed. This simple act of service defined his future here.\n\n5. Just last week, waiting for the 38R bus in the pre-dawn darkness, Dmitri felt a moment of profound calm. The streetlights blurred in the damp air as he thought about his first client of the day. He wasn't heading to a prestigious job, but to make sure Mr. Chen took his medication. He clutched his worn transit pass, a ticket to a life of small, necessary acts. In that quiet moment, he felt not the sting of ambition unfulfilled, but the solid, grounding weight of his own usefulness."
